<p>Done for you SEO sounds simple. Someone else handles your search rankings while you run your business. But 65% of small businesses that hire an SEO provider still struggle to measure whether it works.</p>
<p>The problem is not the concept. The problem is that most businesses buy done for you SEO without understanding what they are paying for, what results look like, or how to tell a good provider from a bad one. That gap costs the average small business $12,000 to $36,000 per year in agency retainers alone.</p>
<p>This guide covers everything you need to evaluate, choose, and get results from done for you SEO. No jargon. No sales pitch. Just the data and frameworks that matter.</p>
<p>We have published 3,500+ SEO articles across 70+ industries. We see what works, what fails, and what most providers never tell their clients. This guide is built on that experience.</p>
<p>Here is what you will learn:</p>
<ul>
<li>What done for you SEO actually includes (and what it should include)</li>
<li>How it compares to DIY SEO and hiring an in-house team</li>
<li>What realistic pricing looks like in 2026</li>
<li>The red flags that signal a bad provider</li>
<li>What to expect month by month after signing up</li>
<li>When done for you SEO is not the right fit for your business</li>
</ul>
<h2>What Done for You SEO Actually Means</h2>
<p>The term "done for you SEO" covers any arrangement where an external provider handles your search engine optimization. But the scope varies wildly between providers.</p>
<p>At one end, you get a freelancer who writes 4 blog posts per month. At the other, you get a full-service team handling content, technical SEO, link building, local optimization, and monthly reporting. Same label. Completely different service.</p>
<h3>The Core Components</h3>
<p>A legitimate done for you SEO service should cover 5 areas:</p>
