<p>Some providers also include link building, local SEO (Google Business Profile optimization), and social media. Others charge extra for each.</p>
<h3>What "Done for You" Should Mean</h3>
<p>The word "done" matters. If a provider sends you a Google Doc and asks you to publish it, that is not done for you. If they require you to log into your CMS, upload images, write meta descriptions, or share posts on social media, they have outsourced the busywork back to you.</p>
<p>True done for you SEO means the provider handles strategy, execution, and publishing. You review results. That is it.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="DIY vs done for you vs in-house SEO comparison" src="/images/blog/done-for-you-seo-comparison.webp" /></p>
<h2>Done for You SEO vs DIY vs In-House</h2>
