<h2>How to Choose a Done for You SEO Provider</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.hirewithnear.com/blog/seo-outsourcing-statistics">75% of large enterprises</a> already outsource SEO. The challenge is not finding a provider. It is finding the right one.</p>
<h3>The 5-Question Vetting Framework</h3>
<p>Ask these questions before signing any contract:</p>
<p><strong>1. "What will you deliver in month 1?"</strong></p>
<p>A good provider maps out the first 30 days in detail. Keyword research, site audit, content calendar, first batch of articles. A bad provider says "we will assess your situation."</p>
<p><strong>2. "How do you build content strategy?"</strong></p>
<p>The answer should involve <a href="/glossary/keyword-research/">keyword research</a>, competitor analysis, and <a href="/blog/build-topical-authority/">topical authority</a> mapping. If they skip strategy and jump straight to writing, the content will rank for nothing.</p>
<p><strong>3. "Can I see work you have done for a similar business?"</strong></p>
<p>Request case studies with real URLs, not anonymized screenshots. Check those URLs in Ahrefs or Semrush to verify the claims.</p>
<p><strong>4. "Who writes the content?"</strong></p>
<p><a href="https://ahrefs.com/blog/search-traffic-study/">96.55% of pages get zero traffic from Google</a>. Most of those pages have generic, thin content. Know whether your provider uses experienced writers, AI with human editing, or fully automated output.</p>
<p><strong>5. "What happens if I cancel?"</strong></p>
<p>Understand the contract terms. Do you keep the content? Do you keep website access? Are there cancellation penalties? A provider confident in their results does not need a 12-month lock-in.</p>
