<h2>Red Flags That Signal a Bad SEO Provider</h2>
<p>Google maintains an <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/fundamentals/do-i-need-seo">official guide on hiring SEO professionals</a>. Their first warning: "Be wary of SEOs that claim to guarantee rankings."</p>
<p>Here are the specific red flags to watch for:</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="8 red flags when hiring a done for you SEO provider" src="/images/blog/done-for-you-seo-red-flags.webp" /></p>
<h3>Guaranteed Rankings</h3>
<p>No one can guarantee a #1 position on Google. Google's algorithm uses over 200 ranking factors and changes thousands of times per year. Any provider that promises specific positions is either lying or using tactics that will get your site penalized.</p>
<h3>No Transparency on Methods</h3>
<p>If a provider will not explain what they do each month, they may be doing nothing. Or they may be using black-hat tactics like link farms, private blog networks, or content spinning. Ask for a monthly deliverable report with specific URLs, word counts, and keyword targets.</p>
<h3>Suspiciously Low Pricing</h3>
<p>An agency that charges $200 per month for "full SEO" is almost certainly outsourcing everything to the cheapest labor available. The output will be generic, unoptimized content that wastes your time and money.</p>
<h3>Long Lock-In Contracts</h3>
<p>Month-to-month billing signals confidence. A 12-month contract with early termination fees signals a provider who knows clients leave after seeing poor results.</p>
<h3>Vanity Metrics in Reporting</h3>
<p>Watch for reports that focus on domain authority, backlink count, or keyword rankings without connecting them to traffic, leads, or revenue. Metrics that do not tie to business outcomes are distractions. Use our <a href="/tools/seo-roi-calculator/">SEO ROI calculator</a> to check whether your results translate to real value.</p>
<h3>The Red Flag Checklist</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Guarantees specific rankings or traffic numbers</li>
<li>[ ] Refuses to show past client results with real URLs</li>
<li>[ ] Cannot explain their content strategy in plain language</li>
<li>[ ] Requires 6-12 month contracts with cancellation penalties</li>
<li>[ ] Reports on vanity metrics without business outcomes</li>
<li>[ ] Uses outsourced link building from unknown sources</li>
<li>[ ] Delivers content without keyword targeting or SEO optimization</li>
<li>[ ] Takes weeks to respond to questions or concerns</li>
</ul>
<p>If a provider triggers 3 or more of these flags, move on.</p>
<h2>What to Expect Month by Month</h2>
<p>SEO compounds over time. The biggest mistake businesses make with done for you SEO is expecting month-1 results from a month-6 strategy. Here is a realistic timeline.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Done for you SEO results timeline month by month" src="/images/blog/done-for-you-seo-timeline.webp" /></p>
<h3>Month 1: Foundation</h3>
<p>Your provider audits your site, conducts keyword research, and builds a content calendar. First articles get published. No ranking changes yet. This month is about strategy, not results.</p>
<p><strong>Deliverables:</strong> Site audit, keyword map, content calendar, 8-30 articles published.</p>
<h3>Months 2-3: Indexing and Early Signals</h3>
<p>Google indexes new content. You start seeing impressions in Google Search Console. Some long-tail keywords begin ranking on pages 2 and 3. This is normal. <a href="https://firstpagesage.com/reports/seo-roi-statistics-fc/">SEO break-even typically takes 6 to 12 months</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Deliverables:</strong> Continued publishing, technical fixes from audit, first performance report.</p>
<h3>Months 4-6: Traction</h3>
<p>Long-tail keywords move to page 1. Organic traffic increases measurably. Internal links between posts create <a href="/blog/build-topical-authority/">topical authority</a> signals that Google rewards. This is where the compounding effect starts.</p>
<p><strong>Deliverables:</strong> Content updates, new keyword targets, link building begins.</p>
<h3>Months 7-12: Compounding Growth</h3>
<p>Established content ranks for multiple keyword variations. Older posts gain authority as new posts link to them. Traffic grows month over month without additional effort on each individual post.</p>
<p>The <a href="https://firstpagesage.com/reports/seo-roi-statistics-fc/">median SEO ROI is 748%</a>. That means $7.48 returned for every $1 invested. But that return concentrates in months 7 through 24. Businesses that quit at month 4 never see it.</p>
<h3>Month 12+: Maintenance and Expansion</h3>
<p>At this stage, your provider shifts focus from building authority to defending rankings and expanding into new keyword clusters. Content refreshes keep existing posts current. New content targets higher-competition terms you could not rank for at month 1.</p>
