<h2>When Done for You SEO Is Not the Right Fit</h2>
<p>Done for you SEO works for most businesses. But not all. Here are the exceptions.</p>
<h3>You Have Zero Online Presence</h3>
<p>If your website does not exist yet, SEO is premature. Build the site first. Then start SEO. A provider who sells SEO before you have a functional website is selling you a roof before the walls are up.</p>
<h3>Your Business Model Does Not Benefit From Search</h3>
<p>Some businesses run entirely on referrals, trade shows, or direct outreach. If your customers do not search Google to find services like yours, SEO spend goes nowhere. Verify demand first. Search your core service terms in Google. If nobody is searching, organic traffic will not help.</p>
<h3>You Need Results This Week</h3>
<p>SEO takes 3 to 6 months for early traction. If you need leads next Tuesday, run paid ads. Done for you SEO is a long-term investment, not an emergency fix.</p>
<h3>You Want Full Creative Control</h3>
<p>Done for you means someone else writes your content. If your brand voice requires personal storytelling, technical depth that only your team can provide, or editorial review of every sentence, a fully outsourced model may frustrate you. Consider a hybrid approach where you provide the expertise and a <a href="/blog/seo-content-writing/">content writing service</a> handles the optimization and publishing.</p>
